00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:46.860
because you've already formed
the perception that everything
in that department is the lowest
price in town.

00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:52.330
>> SMITH: And maybe it's not.
>> No, it's not.
No, I can tell you it's not.
I can tell you from experience

00:22:52.330 --> 00:22:53.660
it's not.

00:22:57.260 --> 00:23:07.160
>> SMITH: Back in the 1950s, Sam
Walton dreamed up the idea of an
eye-popping opening price point.
>> Sam had an old Ford pickup

00:23:07.160 --> 00:23:13.530
truck, and he'd go down the road
and buy ladies' panties and sell
them at a ridiculous low price,
you know, ten for a buck, or

00:23:13.530 --> 00:23:21.400
something like that.
>> SMITH: And it worked.
Sam got a jump on bigger rivals
by targeting territory they

00:23:21.400 --> 00:23:28.600
ignored, building his early
stores near small towns in the
south.
>> One thing you have to think

00:23:28.600 --> 00:23:35.700
about in the history about us is
that we are a company that
hasn't been that long ago that
we were a regional player.

00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:41.900
What we found is we had to
compete with, as a regional
player, those that were national
players.

00:23:41.900 --> 00:23:48.260
How do we do that?
We had to go overseas to find
products in some cases.
In the '70s and '80s, Sam Walton

00:23:48.260 --> 00:23:54.160
would travel overseas looking
for goods that would sell in our
stores.
>> SMITH: Despite Wal-Mart's

00:23:54.160 --> 00:24:02.330
much publicized Buy American
