their cost on the product.

00:34:21.530 --> 00:34:29.000
And it's very high pressure.
>> SMITH: Have you ever been in
that situation where you had to
bid, three or four people in the

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:32.660
same room?
>> Yeah, I have.
One of the things that I was
involved in, they were

00:34:32.660 --> 00:34:42.160
inexpensive, less than... they
were probably, at the most,
maybe less than a dollar.
>> SMITH: So they're pounding

00:34:42.160 --> 00:34:47.900
for a few pennies.
>> Yeah, they're only pounding
for, in a lot of cases, just one
penny, in fact.

00:34:47.900 --> 00:34:52.600
>> SMITH: Now, the argument is
that this is getting a better
deal for the consumer.
Do you buy that or do you say...

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:57.260
>> No, it's getting a better
deal for the retailer or the
importer.
>> SMITH: For the Wal-Mart.

00:34:57.260 --> 00:35:03.400
>> Yeah, for the Wal-Mart, for
the Targets, whoever does it.
>> SMITH: I'd heard about the
Chinese producing cheap, low-end

00:35:03.400 --> 00:35:11.500
consumer goods.
